# MotoView Project Rules

MotoView is a **Motoko-native, server-driven UI framework for Internet Computer (ICP) canisters**.
You write `.mview` files (template markup + Motoko in one file, Blazor/Blade/LiveView feel). It
**compiles to Motoko** and deploys with `dfx`. Mental model: rendering is a query, events are
updates, the browser syncs through versioned UI batches.

## Hard rule: NO Node / npm / JS build tooling (core selling point)

Never suggest or scaffold `package.json`, npm/yarn/pnpm/npx, Webpack/Vite/Rollup/esbuild/Babel,
React/Vue/Svelte/agent-js, or any hand-written application JavaScript. The **only** browser code is
the framework's own Rust→WebAssembly client (`/motoview.wasm`, `/motoview.js`, `/motoview.css`);
the `motoview.js` glue ships with the framework — app developers never write or edit browser JS.

## Stack

- Compiler: Rust crate → `motoview` binary (installed via `cargo`), parses `.mview`, emits Motoko.
- Runtime: Motoko library in `runtime/` (mops package `motoview`); serves HTTP from the canister.
- Dev/deploy: `dfx` (DFINITY SDK).
- Browser: Rust→WASM (brain: adaptive polling state machine, protocol, batch interpretation, event
  sequencing) + tiny JS glue (hands: DOM/fetch/timer + focus/scroll/input preservation).

## Project layout

`src/Pages/*.mview`, `src/Layouts/*.mview`, `src/Components/*.mview`, `src/Services/*.mo`,
`src/Models/*.mo`, `motoview.json`, `dfx.json`, `mops.toml`. Compiler output is a Motoko actor
(`src/main.mo` / `src/Generated/`).

## CLI

```bash
motoview new <app>        # scaffold
motoview build            # compile .mview -> Motoko
motoview dev              # build + dfx deploy + watch (local)
motoview compile <file>   # compile one file (debugging)
```

Prereqs: `dfx`, `rustup` + `wasm32-unknown-unknown` target, `wasm-opt` (binaryen). Add runtime via
mops `motoview` or local path dep in `dfx.json` args (`--package motoview ../../runtime/src`).

## `.mview` directives

- Structure: `@page "/path"` (also `"/products/{id}"`, typed `"/orders/{id:Nat}"`), `@layout NAME`,
  `@title EXPR`, `@description EXPR`, `@canonical EXPR`, `@meta`, `@head`, `@section "name" { }`,
  `@yield`, `@slot "name"`, `@authorize` / `@authorize role="Admin"`.
- Code/style: `@code { ...Motoko... }`, `@style { ...css... }`, `@theme { tokens }`.
- Control/output: `@if EXPR { } else { }`, `@for X in EXPR { }`, `@switch EXPR { case #Variant { } }`,
  inline `@count` / `@user.name` / `@(expr)`, `@effect Focus("#x")`/`ScrollTo`/`Toast`, `@animate`.

## Events

`@click="handler"`, `@click="handler(arg)"`, `@submit="handler"`, `@input="handler"`, `@change`.
Handler args are evaluated **server-side at render time** and baked into `data-mv-arg*`; the WASM
client forwards `handlerId` + args; the server dispatches to typed Motoko functions. Developer just
writes `@click="save"`.

```razor
@page "/counter"
@code {
  var count : Nat = 0;
  func increment() { count += 1 };
}
<h1>Count: @count</h1>
<Button kind="primary" @click="increment">Add one</Button>
```

## Forms, validation, security

`<form @submit="send" secure>` with `bind="@model.field"`. The `secure` attribute mints a signed
token (**HMAC-SHA256**) binding path + handler + caller principal + nonce + expiry + field-schema
hash; the server re-derives the MAC and rejects mismatches, expired tokens, and replays (SHA-256 +
HMAC implemented in Motoko, verified against standard vectors). Validate in handlers — never on the
client:

```motoko
validate model {
  name required "Name is required";
  email required email;
  price min 1 "Price must be at least 1";
};
```

Errors return in the batch and re-render. Use `<ValidationSummary />` and per-field errors.

## Components

Capitalized tags are components; app components in `src/Components/*.mview` declare
`param name : T [= default]`. Prefer built-in semantic components over class-string soup:
`Button` (kind, size), `Card` (title), `Alert` (type), `Badge` (type), `InputText`/`InputEmail`/
`InputNumber`/`TextArea` (name, label, bind, required, minLength), `ValidationSummary`, `Table`,
`PageHeader`, `Grid` (columns).

## Protocol (`motoview/1`)

- First load: `GET /page` → server-rendered HTML; content in `<div id="mv-root">`.
- Sync: `GET /_motoview/render?path=...&lastBatchId=...` → batch JSON, status
  `changed` | `unchanged` | `redirect` | `validation-error` (`unchanged` omits html when `batchId`
  matched).
- Events: `POST` form-encoded `/_motoview/event` → served by `http_request_update` → new batch
  immediately. `batchId` is a hash of rendered state.
- Adaptive polling: hot ~350ms (~3s after interaction), warm ~2.5s visible, cold ~15s idle, hidden
  ~45s, offline = exponential backoff.
- IC transport (MVP): `http_request` returns `upgrade=true` so everything is served by
  `http_request_update` (avoids query response-certification). Certified query rendering is Roadmap.

## Verified vs Roadmap

VERIFIED end to end: runtime + WASM client + dfx pipeline; counter example deployed to a local
replica and exercised in a real browser (click → event → update → batch → DOM swap), adaptive
polling picks up external changes, state persists; SHA-256/HMAC pass standard vectors. Examples:
todo, contact form, products CRUD.

ROADMAP (do NOT present as working): keyed-region / granular DOM patches, full Internet Identity
login over HTTP, role stores, vetKeys encrypted state, certified query rendering,
desktop/mobile/tablet shells, visual designer, push adapter.

## DO / DON'T

- DO write `.mview` (markup + `@code { }` Motoko); use only the directives, events, and components
  named above; use `<form ... secure>` + `bind` + `validate model { }`; use `dfx`/`motoview` CLI.
- DON'T add Node/npm/bundlers/React/app JavaScript; DON'T invent directives, attributes, flags,
  file names, components, or numbers; DON'T do client-side validation; DON'T edit the framework's
  WASM/JS glue; DON'T claim Roadmap features are implemented.
